AN ACT relating to housing; revising provisions relating to discrimination in
housing; and providing other matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing federal law prohibits certain discriminatory practices relating to housing based
2 on race, color, religion, sex, handicap, familial status or national origin. (42 U.S.C. §§ 3601 et
3 seq.) Under certain circumstances, existing federal regulations provide that housing
4 discrimination may be established based on the discriminatory effect of a practice, even if the
5 practice was not motivated by a discriminatory intent. (24 C.F.R. § 100.500) This is
6 commonly known as the “disparate impact standard.”
7 The Nevada Fair Housing Law: (1) prohibits discrimination in housing on the basis of
8 race, religious creed, color, national origin, disability, sexual orientation, gender identity or
9 expression, ancestry, familial status or sex; and (2) provides a process and remedies to enforce
10 the Nevada Fair Housing Law if a person engages in such discrimination, including the
11 authority to file a complaint with the Nevada Equal Rights Commission and to commence an
12 action in any district court to obtain an injunction and civil damages. (NRS 118.010-118.120)
13 This bill adopts the disparate impact standard for purposes of the Nevada Fair Housing Law.
14 Section 1 of this bill provides that liability may be established for a discriminatory
15 housing practice if: (1) the practice was motivated by a discriminatory intent; or (2) with
16 certain exceptions, the practice was not motivated by a discriminatory intent but the practice
17 actually or predictably results in a [disparate impact] discriminatory effect on a group of
18 persons or creates, increases, reinforces or perpetuates segregated housing patterns because of
19 race, religious creed, color, national origin, disability, sexual orientation, gender identity or
20 expression, ancestry, familial status or sex. Section 1 further provides that there is no liability
21 for a discriminatory housing practice based on the disparate impact standard if, based on
22 evidence that is not hypothetical or speculative: (1) the practice is necessary to achieve one or
23 more substantial, legitimate and nondiscriminatory interests of the respondent; and (2) the
24 interests of the respondent could not be served by another practice that has a less
25 discriminatory effect. Section 1 also provides that the complainant must establish that a

